.TH "get_err_from_table" 9 "get_err_from_table" "May 2021" "Kernel Hacker's Manual" LINUX
.SH NAME
get_err_from_table \- Gets the error message from a table
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B "const char *" get_err_from_table
.BI "(const char *table[] "  ","
.BI "int size "  ","
.BI "int pos "  ");"
.SH ARGUMENTS
.IP "table" 12
table name (array of char *)
.IP "size" 12
number of elements at the table
.IP "pos" 12
position of the element to be returned
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
This is a small routine that gets the pos-th element of a table. If the
element doesn't exist (or it is empty), it returns "reserved".
Instead of calling it directly, the better is to call via the macro
\fBGET_ERR_FROM_TABLE\fP, that automatically checks the table size via
\fBARRAY_SIZE\fP macro
